  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "Yes, O-negative (O-) blood is considered the universal donor for red blood cells. People with O-negative blood can donate red blood cells to individuals of any blood type because O-negative blood does not have any A, B, or Rh antigens on the surface of the red blood cells. This makes it safe for transfusion into patients of any blood type without risking an immune reaction against the donor blood. However, O-negative is not a universal donor for plasma; AB plasma is considered a universal donor for plasma transfusions.",
